="b4-80.4stein"><label>4.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Colin</surname><given-names>Jones</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The Construction of the Hospital Patient,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Finzsch and</surname></name><name><surname>J&#x000fc;tte</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Institutions and Confinement</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>55</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>74</lpage>, <comment>on p. 60</comment></citation></ref><ref id="b5-80.4stein"><label>5.</label><note><p>For these requirements, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3fa94f0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>100</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>114</lpage>, <comment>118&#x02013;19, 130&#x02013;33, 139</comment></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b6-80.4stein"><label>6.</label><note><p>&#x0201c;Nit allein cum morbo gallico, sondern auch cum elephantiasis (SA, Karton VI, no. 47, Prod.86).&#x0201d;</p></note></ref><ref id="b7-80.4stein"><label>7.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3fa96d0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Christoph</surname><given-names>Wirsung</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Artzney Buch</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Heidelberg</publisher-loc>, <year>1586</year>), pp. <fpage>510</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>12</lpage></citation> On the pharmacist Wirsung and his printing business, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f85450"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Hans-J&#x000f6;rg</surname><given-names>K&#x000fc;nast</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Gedruckt in Augsburg: Buchdruck und Buchhandel in Augsburg zwischen 1468 und 1555</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>T&#x000fc;bingen</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Niemeyer</publisher-name>, <year>1997</year>), pp. <fpage>66</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>70</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b8-80.4stein"><label>8.</label><note><p>For these hospitals, their organization and relationship to other health-care institutions, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f855d0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>109</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>12</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="thesis" id="N0x2431540N0x1f856f0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Hammond</surname></name></person-group>, <source>&#x0201c;Origins of Civic Health Care&#x0201d;</source> (n. 3), pp. <fpage>68</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>113</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b9-80.4stein"><label>9.</label><note><p>Nevertheless, we still know woefully little about general consultation practices in the past. See <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f85870"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Roy</surname><given-names>Porter</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The Rise of Physical Examination,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>Medicine and the Five Senses</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>William</surname><given-names>Bynum and </given-names></name><name><surname>Roy</surname><given-names>Porter</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1993</year>), pp. <fpage>179</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>97</lpage></citation>, on p. 179: &#x0201c;it is revealing of both the preference and prejudices of medical historians, and the random survival of evidence, that we know so little about the conduct of routine consultations between practitioners and patients in earlier centuries.&#x0201d;</p></note></ref><ref id="b10-80.4stein"><label>10.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x1f85b10"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Andrew</surname><given-names>Cunningham</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Identifying Diseases in the Past: Cutting through the Gordian Knot,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Asclepio</italic></source>, <year>2002</year>, <volume>54</volume> (<issue>1</issue>): <fpage>13</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>34</lpage></citation> For his earlier reflections on this topic, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f85c30"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Cunningham</surname></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Transforming Plague: The Laboratory and the Identity of Infectious Diseases,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>The Laboratory Revolution in Medicine</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Andrew</surname><given-names>Cunningham and </given-names></name><name><surname>Perry</surname><given-names>Williams</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1992</year>), pp. <fpage>209</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>47</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b11-80.4stein"><label>11.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Cunningham</surname></name></person-group>, <source>&#x0201c;Identifying Diseases&#x0201d;</source> (n. 10), pp. <fpage>15</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>16</lpage></citation></ref><ref id="b12-80.4stein"><label>12.</label><note><p>Therefore all diseases, according to <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f86050"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Cunningham</surname></name></person-group>, possess an &#x0201c;operational identity&#x0201d;: <source>&#x0201c;Identifying Diseases&#x0201d;</source> (n. 10),  p. <fpage>16</fpage></citation>. For this operational identity, see also <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f86170"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Cunningham</surname></name></person-group>, <source>&#x0201c;Transforming Plague&#x0201d;</source> (n. 10), p. <fpage>213</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b13-80.4stein"><label>13.</label><note><p>The recent study by <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f862f0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Arrizabalaga, </surname></name><name><surname>French and</surname></name><name><surname>Henderson</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Great Pox</italic></source><comment>(n. 2)</comment></citation>, is one of the few exeptions that resists this identification. For the authors' reasons, see pp. 1&#x02013;3. For my own agenda, which supports their claims, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f864d0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>13</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>26</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b14-80.4stein"><label>14.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f86650"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Ian</surname><given-names>Maclean</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Logic, Signs and Nature in the Renaissance: The Case of Learned Medicine</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>2002</year>), pp. <fpage>282</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>84</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f86770"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Nancy</surname><given-names>Siraisi</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Disease and Symptom as Problematic Concepts in Renaissance Medicine,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>Res et Verba in the Renaissance</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Eckhard</surname><given-names>Kessler and </given-names></name><name><surname>Ian</surname><given-names>Maclean</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Wiesbaden</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Harrossowitz</publisher-name>, <year>2002</year>), pp. <fpage>217</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>40</lpage></citation> I am grateful to Nancy Siraisi for allowing me to read an earlier draft of this paper.</p></note></ref><ref id="b15-80.4stein"><label>15.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Siraisi</surname></name></person-group>, <source>&#x0201c;Disease and Symptom&#x0201d;</source> (n. 14), p. <fpage>239</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b16-80.4stein"><label>16.</label><note><p>For &#x0201c;styles of reasoning,&#x0201d; see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f86b90"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Ian</surname><given-names>Hacking</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Historical Ontology</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Harvard University Press</publisher-name>, <year>2001</year>), pp. <fpage>178</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>99</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f86cb0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Arnold I.</surname><given-names>Davidson</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Emergence of Sexuality: Historical Epistemology and the Formation of Concept</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Harvard University Press</publisher-name>, <year>2002</year>), esp. chap. 5.</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b17-80.4stein"><label>17.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f86e30"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Colin</surname><given-names>Jones and </given-names></name><name><surname>Laurence</surname><given-names>Brockliss</given-names></name></person-group>, in <source><italic>The Medical World of Early Modern France</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1997</year>), p. <fpage>237</fpage>,</citation> coined this expression to describe the distribution of medical knowledge and practice in early modern France.</p></note></ref><ref id="b18-80.4stein"><label>18.</label><note><p>My findings match those of Gianna Pomata for early modern Bologna: <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f87010"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Gianna</surname><given-names>Pomata</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Contracting a Cure: Patients, Healers and the Law in Early Modern Bologna</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Baltimore</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Johns Hopkins University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1998</year>), p. <fpage>123</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b19-80.4stein"><label>19.</label><note><p>&#x0201c;Just as a good portrait conveys a sense of a person's unique being, so a good medical portrait produces a sketch of the patient's particular collection of conditions, morbid and non-morbid, recent and longstanding, the gifts of nature and the effects of nurture&#x0201d; (<citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f87190"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Brian</surname><given-names>Nance</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Turquet de Mayerne as Baroque Physician: The Art of Medical Portraiture</italic></source> [<publisher-loc>Amsterdam</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Rodopi</publisher-name>, <year>2001</year>], p. <fpage>78</fpage></citation>).</p></note></ref><ref id="b20-80.4stein"><label>20.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f87310"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Michael</surname><given-names>Giesecke</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Der Buchdruck in der Fr&#x000fc;hen Neuzeit: Eine historische Fallstudie &#x000fc;ber die Durchsetzung neuer Informations- und Kommunikationstechniken</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Frankfurt</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Suhrkamp</publisher-name>, <year>1998</year>), pp. <fpage>527</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>41</lpage></citation>. For early modern England, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f87430"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Andrew</surname><given-names>Wear</given-names></name></person-group>,<source><italic>Knowledge and Practice in Early Modern England, 1550&#x02013;1680</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>2000</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f87550"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Mary E.</surname><given-names>Fissell</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Patients, Power, and the Poor in Eighteenth-Century Bristol</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1991</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b21-80.4stein"><label>21.</label><note><p>For a definition of the term &#x0201c;common man,&#x0201d; see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f876d0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Peter</surname><given-names>Blickle</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Deutsche Untertanen: Ein Widerspruch</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>M&#x000fc;nchen</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Beck</publisher-name>, <year>1981</year>), pp. <fpage>15</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>18</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b22-80.4stein"><label>22.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x1f87850"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Adrian</surname><given-names>Johns</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Nature of the Book: Print and Knowledge in the Making</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Chicago</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>University of Chicago Press</publisher-name>, <year>1998</year>), pp. <fpage>31</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>43</lpage></citation> Intersubjective trust as a key element in the making of early modern knowledge about the natural world has been investigated by <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a53e0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Steven</surname><given-names>Shapin</given-names></name></person-group> in his monograph <source><italic>Social History of Truth: Civility and Science in Seventeenth-Century England</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Chicago</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>University of Chicago Press</publisher-name>, <year>1994</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b23-80.4stein"><label>23.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Giesecke</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Buchdruck</italic></source> (n. 20), pp. <fpage>555</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>56</lpage></citation></ref><ref id="b24-80.4stein"><label>24.</label><note><p>For the duties of barber-surgeons, see the contract of the barber-surgeon Hans Gablinger, 14 August 1562, SA, Karton VII, no. 50 (Prod. 1&#x02013;10), Prod. 1. For more information on Augsburg's barber-surgeons, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a56e0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>155</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>62</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="thesis" id="N0x2431540N0x22a5800"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Hammond</surname></name></person-group>, <source>&#x0201c;Origins of Civic Health Care&#x0201d;</source><comment>(n. 3), pp.</comment><fpage>74</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>75</lpage>, <comment>166&#x02013;80</comment></citation>; <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x22a5920"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Robert</surname><given-names>Hoffmann</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Die Augsburger B&#x000e4;der und das Handwerk der Bader,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Zeitschrift des historischen Vereins f&#x000fc;r Schwaben</italic></source>, <year>1885</year>, <volume>12</volume> : <fpage>1</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>33</lpage></citation>. For a more general discussion of this professional group in Germany, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a5a40"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Sabine</surname><given-names>Sander</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Handwerkschirurgen: Sozialgeschichte einer verdr&#x000e4;ngten Berufsgruppe</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>G&#x000f6;ttingen</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Vanderhoeck &#x00026; Ruprecht</publisher-name>, <year>1989</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b25-80.4stein"><label>25.</label><note><p>For the duties of learned physicians, see the contract of Doctor Daniel Zeller, 19 November 1562, SA, Karton VII, no. 50, Prod. 1.</p></note></ref><ref id="b26-80.4stein"><label>26.</label><note><p>For their daily interaction, which included occasional struggle over issues of professional hierarchy, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a5c20"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>203</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>61</lpage></citation>. <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x22a5d40"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Harold</surname><given-names>Cook</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Good Advice and Little Medicine: The Professional Authority of Early Modern English Physicians,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>J. Brit. Stud.</italic></source>, <year>1994</year>, <volume>33</volume> : <fpage>1</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>31</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">11639268</pub-id></citation>, has argued for a very similar division of labor and authority between physicians and surgeons in early modern London. This also seems to have been the case for early modern Bologna, according to <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a5e60"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Pomata</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Contracting a Cure</italic></source> (n. 18), p. <fpage>128</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b27-80.4stein"><label>27.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Michel</surname><given-names>Foucault</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Birth of the Clinic: An Archaeology of Medical Perception</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>New York</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Vintage Books</publisher-name>, <year>1994</year>), p. <fpage>90</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b28-80.4stein"><label>28.</label><note><p>For this, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a6160"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Margaret</surname><given-names>Pelling</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Contagion/Germ Theory/Specificity,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>Companion Encyclopaedia of the History of Medicine</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>W. F.</surname><given-names>Bynum and </given-names></name><name><surname>Roy</surname><given-names>Porter</given-names></name></person-group>, vol. <volume>1</volume> (<publisher-loc>London</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Routledge</publisher-name>, <year>1993</year>), pp. <fpage>309</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>34</lpage>, <comment>on p. 314</comment></citation>. In regard to the emergence of our modern disease entities and the problematic of applying these to the investigation of past diseases, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a63a0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Thomas</surname><given-names>Schlich</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Die Herstellung wissenschaftlicher Fakten als Thema der Geschichtsforschung,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>Medizingeschichte: Aufgaben, Probleme, Perspektiven</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Thomas</surname><given-names>Schlich and </given-names></name><name><surname>Norbert</surname><given-names>Paul</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Frankfurt</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Campus Verlag</publisher-name>, <year>1998</year>), pp. <fpage>107</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>29</lpage>, <comment>on p. 114</comment></citation>. For retrospective diagnosis, see also <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a65e0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Karl-Heinz</surname><given-names>Leven</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Krankheiten&#x02014;historische Deutung versus retrospektive Diagnose,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Medizingeschichte: Aufgaben, Probleme, Perspektiven</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Thomas</surname><given-names>Schlich and </given-names></name><name><surname>Norbert</surname><given-names>Paul</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Frankfurt</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Campus Verlag</publisher-name>, <year>1998</year>), pp. <fpage>153</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>85</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b29-80.4stein"><label>29.</label><note><p>For the following, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a6880"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Lester</surname><given-names>King</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;What Is Disease?&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>Concepts of Health and Disease: Interdisciplinary Perspective</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Arthur</surname><given-names>Caplan</given-names></name></person-group> et al. (<publisher-loc>Reading, Mass.</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Addison-Wesley</publisher-name>, <year>1981</year>), pp. <fpage>107</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>18</lpage>, <comment>on p. 112</comment></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b30-80.4stein"><label>30.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a6ac0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Wear</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Knowledge and Practice</italic></source> (n. 20), p. <fpage>127</fpage></citation> Not all languages, however, distinguish between &#x0201c;objective signs&#x0201d; and &#x0201c;subjective symptoms&#x0201d;; in the German language, for example, the terms &#x0201c;sign&#x0201d; and &#x0201c;symptom&#x0201d; are used synonymously.</p></note></ref><ref id="b31-80.4stein"><label>31.</label><note><p>Foucault has argued that this reorganization of the medical gaze slowly emerges during the eighteenth century: &#x0201c;The formation of the clinical method was bound up with emergence of the doctor's gaze into the field of signs and symptoms. The recognition of its constituent rights involved the effacement of their absolute distinction and the postulate that henceforth the signifier (sign and symptom) would be entirely transparent for the signified, which would appear, without concealment or residue, in the most pristine reality, and that the essence of the signified&#x02014;the heart of the disease&#x02014;would be entirely exhausted in the intelligible syntax of the signifier&#x0201d; (<citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a6c40"><source><italic>Birth of the Clinic</italic></source> [n. 27], p. <fpage>91</fpage></citation>).</p></note></ref><ref id="b32-80.4stein"><label>32.</label><note><p>On early modern medical semiotics, see the already mentioned works of Nancy Siraisi and Ian Maclean (n. 14). For a more general account of medical semiotics, see the classic study by <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a6d00"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>F. C.</surname><given-names>Crookshank</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The Importance of a Theory of Signs and a Critique of Language in the Study of Medicine,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>The Meaning of Meaning: a Study of the Influence of Language upon Thought and the Science of Symolism, by C. K. Ogden and I. A. Richards with supplementary essays from B. Malinowsky and F. C. Crookshank</italic></source>, <series>7th</series> ed. (<publisher-loc>New York</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Harcourt, Brace</publisher-name>, <year>1945</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a6e20"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>C. M.</surname><given-names>MacBryde and</given-names></name><name><surname>R S</surname><given-names>Backlow</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Signs and Symptoms: Applied Pathologic Physiology and Clinical Interpretation</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Philadelphia</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Lippincott</publisher-name>, <year>1970</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a6fa0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Thomas A.</surname><given-names>Sebeok</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Signs</italic></source>, <series>2nd</series> ed. (<publisher-loc>Toronto</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>University of Toronto Press</publisher-name>, <year>2001</year>), pp. <fpage>65</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>82</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x22a70c0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Jakob von</surname><given-names>Uexhull</given-names></name></person-group><article-title>&#x0201c;Semiotics and Medicine,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Semiotica</italic></source>, <year>1982</year>, <volume>38</volume> : <fpage>205</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>15</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x22a71e0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Antoinette</surname><given-names>Stettler</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Zeichen lesen und Zeichen deuten,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Gesnerus</italic></source>, <year>1987</year>, <volume>44</volume> : <fpage>33</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>45</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">3301545</pub-id></citation>. For anthropological views, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a7300"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Kathryn Vance</surname><given-names>Staiano</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>Interpreting Signs of Illness: A Case Study in Medical Semiotics</article-title> (<publisher-loc>Berlin</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>de Gruyter</publisher-name>, <year>1986</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a7420"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Byron J.</surname><given-names>Good</given-names></name></person-group>,  <source><italic>Medicine, Rationality, and Experience: An Anthropological Perspective</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1994</year>), pp. <fpage>88</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>115</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b33-80.4stein"><label>33.</label><note><p>&#x0201c;Das ist ein ding das etwas durch die sinnlichkeit verstehen gibt&#x0201d; (<citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a75a0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Lorenz</surname><given-names>Fries</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Spiegel der Artzney</italic></source> [<publisher-loc>Strasburg</publisher-loc>, <year>1532</year>], fol. 39)</citation>. For Lorenz Fries, see the medical dissertation by <citation citation-type="thesis" id="N0x2431540N0x22a76c0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Rudolf Christian Ludwig</surname><given-names>&#x000d6;lschlegel</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Studien zu Lorenz Fries und seinem &#x0201c;Spiegel der Arznei&#x0201d;</italic></source> (med. diss., T&#x000fc;bingen, <year>1985</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b34-80.4stein"><label>34.</label><note><p>See in particular <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x22a7840"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Suzannah</surname><given-names>Biernoff</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Sight and Embodiment in the Middle Ages</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Basingstoke</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Houndsmills</publisher-name>, <year>2002</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52040"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Carolly</surname><given-names>Erickson</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Medieval Vision: Essays in History and Perception</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>New York</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Oxford University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1976</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b35-80.4stein"><label>35.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Biernoff</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Sight and Embodiment</italic></source> (n. 34), p. <fpage>3</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b36-80.4stein"><label>36.</label><note><p>See <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52340"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>G. E. R.</surname><given-names>Lloyd</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Aristotle: The Growth and Structure of His Thought</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1968</year>)</citation>. On the character of Aristotelian natural philosophy and its early modern critics, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52460"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Keith</surname><given-names>Hutchison</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Dormative Virtues, Scholastic Qualities, and the New Philosophies,&#x02019;&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Hist. Sci.</italic></source>, <year>1991</year>, <volume>29</volume> : <fpage>245</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>78</lpage></citation>. For the many different versions of Aristotelianism, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52580"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Charles B.</surname><given-names>Schmitt</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Aristotle in the Renaissance</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Harvard University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1983</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b37-80.4stein"><label>37.</label><note><p>&#x0201c;Dz man in jede kunst anfahen soll von den dingen / die uns im kuendlichsten sind&#x0201d; (<citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52700"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Fries</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Spiegel der Artzney</italic></source><comment>[n. 33], fol. 39)</comment></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b38-80.4stein"><label>38.</label><note><p>&#x0201c;Die natur ist nicht anders dann ein eingepfanzte krafft/ aller der dingen die under dem Mon seind / welche krafft eines yeden ding im selbst ein gleichformig macht oder begert z&#x000f9; machen&#x0201d; (<citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52880"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Fries</surname></name></person-group>,<source><italic>Spiegel der Artzney</italic></source>, <comment>fol. 3<sup>r</sup>)</comment></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b39-80.4stein"><label>39.</label><note><p>It was not until the seventeenth century that the notion of a heliocentric cosmos, put forward by the astronomer Nicolaus Copernicus in 1543, gained wider acceptance. For the slow acceptance of Copernican ideas, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52a00"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Robert S.</surname><given-names>Westman</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The Copernicans and the Churches,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>God and Nature: Historical Essays on the Encounter between Christianity and Science</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>David C.</surname><given-names>Lindberg and </given-names></name><name><surname>Ronald L</surname><given-names>Numbers</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Berkeley and Los Angeles</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>University of California Press</publisher-name>, <year>1986</year>), pp. <fpage>76</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>113</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b40-80.4stein"><label>40.</label><note><p>In a collective sense, the term &#x0201c;physis&#x0201d; or &#x0201c;nature&#x0201d; denotes the ensemble of all natural objects that possessed such a nature; see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52ca0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>David C.</surname><given-names>Lindberg</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Beginnings of Western Science: The European Scientific Tradition in Philosophical, Religious, and Institutional Context, 600 B.C. to A.D. 1450</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Chicago</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>University of Chicago Press</publisher-name>, <year>1992</year>), p. <fpage>281</fpage></citation>. For a medical perspective on nature, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52dc0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Max</surname><given-names>Neuburger</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;An Historical Study of the Concept of Nature from a Medical Standpoint,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Isis</italic></source>, <year>1944</year>, <volume>35</volume> : <fpage>16</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>28</lpage></citation>. For a more general account, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d52ee0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Leonard</surname><given-names>Barkan</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Nature's Work of Art: The Human Body as Image of the World</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>New Haven</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Yale University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1975</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53000"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Lorraine</surname><given-names>Daston</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The Nature of Nature in Early Modern Europe,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Configurations</italic></source>, <year>1998</year>, <volume>6</volume> : <fpage>149</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>72</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">11619984</pub-id></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b41-80.4stein"><label>41.</label><note><p>On von Hutten and his disease, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53180"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Michael</surname><given-names>Peschke</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Ulrich von Hutten (1488&#x02013;1523) als Kranker und als medizinischer Schriftsteller</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cologne</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Forschungsstelle des Instituts der Geschichte der Medizin in der Universit&#x000e4;t zu K&#x000f6;ln</publisher-name>, <year>1985</year>)</citation>. For the history of the wood guaiacum, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d532a0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Patricia</surname><given-names>V&#x000f6;ttinger-Pletz</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Lignum Sanctum: Zur therapeutischen Verwendung des Guajak vom 16. bis zum 20. Jahrhundert</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Frankfurt</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Govi</publisher-name>, <year>1990</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b42-80.4stein"><label>42.</label><note><p>The tract was originally published in Latin but was soon translated by Thomas Murner into German: <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53420"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Ulrich von</surname><given-names>Hutten</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Ulrich vo[n] Hutten eins teutschen Ritters von der wunderbarliche[n] artzney des holtz Guaiacu[m] genant, und wie man die Frantzosen oder blattere[n] heilen sol &#x02026; </italic></source> (Augsburg, <year>1519</year>)</citation>, reprinted in <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53540"><person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Eduard</surname><given-names>B&#x000f6;cking</given-names></name></person-group>, ed., <source><italic>Ulrich von Hutten. Schriften</italic></source>, vol. <volume>5</volume> (<publisher-loc>Leipzig</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Teubner</publisher-name>, <year>1861</year>), pp. <fpage>399</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>497</lpage>; here, pp. 408&#x02013;9.</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b43-80.4stein"><label>43.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Nance</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Turquet de Mayerne</italic></source> (n. 19), p. <fpage>115</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b44-80.4stein"><label>44.</label><note><p>For the importance of this traditional opposition for the professional hierarchies in early modern medicine, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53840"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Pomata</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Contracting a Cure</italic></source> (n. 18), p. <fpage>132</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b45-80.4stein"><label>45.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d539c0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Barbara</surname><given-names>Duden</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Women Beneath the Skin: A Doctor's Patients in Eighteenth-Century Germany</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Harvard University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1991</year>), p. <fpage>127</fpage></citation>. In her influential study Duden has shown that the understanding of the body as an open space dominated German medical practice until well into the eighteenth century.</p></note></ref><ref id="b46-80.4stein"><label>46.</label><note><p>For a detailed explanation of the process of concoction, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53b40"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Nancy</surname><given-names>Siraisi</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Medieval and Early Renaissance Medicine: An Introduction to Knowledge and Practice</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Chicago</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>University of Chicago Press</publisher-name>, <year>1990</year>), p. <fpage>106</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b47-80.4stein"><label>47.</label><note><p>See <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53cc0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>140</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>52</lpage>, <comment>203&#x02013;39</comment></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b48-80.4stein"><label>48.</label><note><p>For more details on this, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53e40"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Nance</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Turquet de Mayerne</italic></source> (n. 19), pp. <fpage>115</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>16</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b49-80.4stein"><label>49.</label><note><p>For these debates and their outcome in more detail, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3d53fc0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>140</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>52</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b50-80.4stein"><label>50.</label><note><p>My own research revealed that most learned physicians in sixteenth-century Augsburg rejected Paracelsian ideas. This might explain why the archival records of the pox hospital show no influence of his ideas. For the nonacceptance of Paracelsian ideas in Augsburg, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x3d54140"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Joachim</surname><given-names>Telle</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Wolfgang Thalhauser: Zu Leben und Werk eines Augsburger Stadtarztes und seinen Beziehungen zu Paracelsus und Schwenkfeld,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Medizinhistorisches Journal</italic></source>, <year>1972</year>, <volume>7</volume> : <fpage>1</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>30</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">11609764</pub-id></citation>. On Paracelsian infuence in Augsburg, see also <citation citation-type="thesis" id="N0x2431540N0x3d54260"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Hammond</surname></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Origins of Civic Health Care&#x0201d;</article-title> (n. 3), pp. <fpage>226</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>37</lpage></citation>. For Paracelsus's writings on the pox, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x3d54380"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Gundolf</surname><given-names>Keil and </given-names></name><name><surname>Willem F</surname><given-names>Daems</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Paracelsus und die &#x02018;Franzosen&#x02019;: Betrachtungen zur Venerologie Hohenheims, I: Pathologie und nosologisches Konzept,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Nova Acta Paracelsica</italic></source>, <year>1977</year>, <volume>9</volume> : <fpage>99</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>151</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b51-80.4stein"><label>51.</label><note><p>For an introduction to early modern therapeutics, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42dddc0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Siraisi</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Medieval and Early Renaissance Medicine</italic></source> (n. 46), pp. <fpage>115</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>52</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b52-80.4stein"><label>52.</label><note><p>For the guaiacum cure in the municipal French-disease hospital, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42ddf40"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankeit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>143</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>52</lpage></citation>. For sixteenth-century anonymous instructions on how to prepare guaiacum, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42de060"><source><italic>Hienach volgt ain bevert recept von ainem holtz genannt Guaiacanum wechst in Antilles in ainer Insel gehaissen la isola spagola: Fast hailsam f&#x000fc;r all alt sch&#x000e4;den vnd die kranckhait der Frantzosen</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Augsburg</publisher-loc>, <year>1519</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42de0c0"><source><italic>Ein clarer bericht wie man alte schaden/ l&#x000f6;cher und b&#x000fc;len heylen soll mit dem holtz Guaiaco</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Strasburg</publisher-loc>, <year>1525</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b53-80.4stein"><label>53.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42de180"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Walter</surname><given-names>Ryff</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>New erfundne/ heylsame/ und bew&#x000e4;rte artzney/ gewusse hilff unnd radt/ nit allein die Frantzosen oder b&#x000f6;sen blatern/ &#x02026; bissher f&#x000fc;r vnheylbar geacht worden/ gr&#x000fc;ndlicher vnd gentzlicher zu vertreiben/ heylen vnd Curieren</italic></source> (Strasburg, <year>1559</year>)</citation>, fol. 505<sup>v</sup>. Ryff's treatise was a translation of an earlier Latin tract published in 1537 by the papal surgeon Alfonso Ferri. For a recent reappraisal of Ryff's enormous production, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42de2a0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>William</surname><given-names>Eamon</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Science and the Secrets of Nature: Books on Secrets in Medieval and Early Modern Culture</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Princeton</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Princeton University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1994</year>), pp. <fpage>96</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>98</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b54-80.4stein"><label>54.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42de420"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Joseph</surname><given-names>Schmid</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Kurtzer iedoch Gewisser bericht, dreyer Erblicher kranckheiten, al&#x003b2; da sein, die Pest, Frantzosen, vnd Scharbock, wie sie m&#x000f6;gen curirt werden</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Augsburg</publisher-loc>, <year>1667</year>), pp. <fpage>173</fpage>, 203</citation>. On Joseph Schmid, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x42de540"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Ute</surname><given-names>Ecker-Offenh&#x000e4;user</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Handwerkschirurg und Schriftsteller in Augsburg im 17. Jahrhundert,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Medizin, Geschichte und Gesellschaft</italic></source>, <year>1996</year>, <volume>15</volume> : <fpage>117</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>39</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b55-80.4stein"><label>55.</label><note><p>For the mercury cure at the Augsburg hospitals, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42de6c0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>209</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>12</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b56-80.4stein"><label>56.</label><note><p>See <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42de840"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>von Hutten</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Holtz Guaiacum</italic></source> (n. 42), p. <fpage>409</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b57-80.4stein"><label>57.</label><note><p>Blatterhaus, Ordnung von 1576, SA.</p></note></ref><ref id="b58-80.4stein"><label>58.</label><note><p>For ancient and early modern discussions of mercury, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x42dea20"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Erna</surname><given-names>Lesky</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Von Schmier-und R&#x000e4;ucherkuren zur modernen Syphilistherapie,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Ciba-Zeitschrift</italic></source>, <year>1959</year>, <volume>8</volume> : <fpage>3174</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>89</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x42deb40"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>William</surname><given-names>Abramowitz</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Historical Points of Interest in the Mode of Action and Ill Effects of Mercury,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Bull. N.Y. Acad. Med.</italic></source>, <year>1978</year>, <volume>56</volume> : <fpage>95</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>705</lpage></citation>; <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42dec60"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Owsei</surname><given-names>Temkin</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Therapeutic Trends and the Treatment of Syphilis before 1900,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>The Double Face of Janus</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Baltimore</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Johns Hopkins University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1977</year>), pp. <fpage>518</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>24</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b59-80.4stein"><label>59.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Schmid</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Kurtzer bericht</italic></source> (n. 54), p. <fpage>202</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b60-80.4stein"><label>60.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42def60"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Franz</surname><given-names>Renner</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Ein new wol gegr&#x000fc;ndet n&#x000fc;tzlichs vnnd haylsams handtb&#x000fc;chlein</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>N&#x000fc;rnberg</publisher-loc>, <year>1559</year>), <comment>fol. 30<sup>r</sup></comment></citation>. The book was first published in 1548 and was such a success that it consequently went through several editions.</p></note></ref><ref id="b61-80.4stein"><label>61.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Tobias</surname><given-names>Knobloch</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>De Lue Venerea: Von den Frantzosen kurtzer Bericht</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Giessen</publisher-loc>, <year>1620</year>), p. <fpage>32</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b62-80.4stein"><label>62.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Schmid</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Kurtzer bericht</italic></source> (n. 54), p. <fpage>146</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b63-80.4stein"><label>63.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Knobloch</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>De Lue Venerea</italic></source> (n. 61), p. <fpage>32</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b64-80.4stein"><label>64.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Renner</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Handtb&#x000fc;chlein</italic></source><comment>(n. 60), fols. 6<sup>r</sup>&#x02014;7<sup>r</sup></comment></citation></ref><ref id="b65-80.4stein"><label>65.</label><note><p>For the Galenic concept of pain, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x42df6e0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Rosa Mar&#x000ed;a Moreno</surname><given-names>Rodr&#x000ed;guez and</given-names></name><name><surname>Luis</surname><given-names>Garc&#x000ed;a-Ballester</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;El dolor en la teor&#x000ed;a y la pr&#x000e1;ctica m&#x000e9;dicas de Galeno,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Dynamis</italic></source>, <year>1982</year>, <volume>2</volume> : <fpage>3</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>24</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">11621614</pub-id></citation>. For a general history of pain, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42df860"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Roselyne</surname><given-names>Rey</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The History of Pain</italic></source>, <series>2nd</series> ed. (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Harvard University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1988</year>)</citation>. For the cultural construction of pain, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42df980"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Elaine</surname><given-names>Scarry</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Body in Pain: The Making and the Unmaking of the World</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Oxford</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Oxford University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1985</year>)</citation>; <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x42dfaa0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Jakob</surname><given-names>Tanner</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;K&#x000f6;rpererfahrung, Schmerz und die Konstruktion des Kulturellen,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Historische Anthropologie</italic></source>, <year>1994</year>, <volume>2</volume> (3): <fpage>489</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>502</lpage></citation>. On pain in relation to early modern plague, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x42dfbc0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Otto</surname><given-names>Ulbricht</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Pesterfahrung: Das Sterben und der Schmerz in der Fr&#x000fc;hen Neuzeit,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Medizin, Geschichte und Gesellschaft</italic></source>, <year>1997</year>, <volume>15</volume> : <fpage>9</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>36</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b66-80.4stein"><label>66.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Fries</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Spiegel der Artzney</italic></source><comment>(n. 33), fol. 39<sup>a</sup></comment></citation></ref><ref id="b67-80.4stein"><label>67.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42dfec0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Alexander</surname><given-names>Seitz</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Ein nutzlich regiment wider die b&#x000f6;sen frantzosen &#x02026;</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Pforzheim</publisher-loc>, <year>1509</year>)</citation>, reprinted in <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42dffe0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Peter</surname><given-names>Ukena</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Alexander Seitz s&#x000e4;mtliche Schriften</italic></source>, vol. <volume>1</volume> (<publisher-loc>G&#x000f6;ttingen</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>de Gruyter</publisher-name>, <year>1970</year>), pp. <fpage>7</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>29</lpage>, <comment>on p. 12</comment></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b68-80.4stein"><label>68.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42e0160"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Alexander</surname><given-names>Seitz</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Ein nutzlich regiment wider die b&#x000f6;sen frantzosen &#x02026;</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Pforzheim</publisher-loc>, <year>1509</year>)</citation>, reprinted in <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x42e0280"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Peter</surname><given-names>Ukena</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Alexander Seitz s&#x000e4;mtliche Schriften</italic></source>, vol. <volume>1</volume> (<publisher-loc>G&#x000f6;ttingen</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>de Gruyter</publisher-name>, <year>1970</year>), pp. <fpage>12</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>13</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b69-80.4stein"><label>69.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Renner</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Handtb&#x000fc;chlein</italic></source><comment>(n. 60), fol. 5<sup>r-v</sup></comment></citation></ref><ref id="b70-80.4stein"><label>70.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Rey</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>History of Pain</italic></source> (n. 65), p. <fpage>27</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b71-80.4stein"><label>71.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Fries</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Spiegel der Artzney</italic></source><comment>(n. 33), fol. 33<sup>v</sup></comment></citation></ref><ref id="b72-80.4stein"><label>72.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Foucault</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Birth of the Clinic</italic></source> (n. 27), p. <fpage>4</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b73-80.4stein"><label>73.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Foucault</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Birth of the Clinic</italic></source> (n. 27), p. <fpage>13</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b74-80.4stein"><label>74.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Nance</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Turquet de Mayerne</italic></source> (n. 19), pp. <fpage>114</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>15</lpage></citation></ref><ref id="b75-80.4stein"><label>75.</label><note><p>For an interesting discussion of this issue in relation to the clinical teaching of the Italian Renaissance physician Giovanni Baptista da Monte, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2063ae0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Jerome</surname><given-names>Bylebyl</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;The Manifest and the Hidden in the Renaissance Clinic,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Bynum and </surname></name><name><surname>Porter</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Medicine and the Five Senses</italic></source> (n. 9), pp. <fpage>40</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>60</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b76-80.4stein"><label>76.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Von Hutten</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Holtz Guaicum</italic></source> (n. 42), p. <fpage>306</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b77-80.4stein"><label>77.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Foucault</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Birth of the Clinic</italic></source> (n. 27), p. <fpage>12</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b78-80.4stein"><label>78.</label><note><p>For the discussion of disease crisis in the work of the French physician Jean Fernel, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2064080"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Ingo Wilhelm</surname><given-names>M&#x000fc;ller</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Humoralpathologie: Physiologische, pathologische und therapeutische Grundlagen der galenischen Medizin</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Heidelberg</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Haug</publisher-name>, <year>1993</year>), p. <fpage>108</fpage></citation>. For the problem of measuring time in medicine, see <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x20641a0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Werner Friedrich</surname><given-names>K&#x000fc;mmel</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Der Puls und das Problem der Zeitmessung in der Geschichte der Medizin,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Medizinhistorisches Journal</italic></source>, <year>1974</year>, <volume>9</volume> : <fpage>1</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>22</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">11610179</pub-id></citation>. For an interesting sociological account of the concept of time in history, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x20642c0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Norbert</surname><given-names>Elias</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>&#x000dc;ber die Zeit</italic></source>, <series>5th</series> ed. (<publisher-loc>Frankfurt</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Suhrkamp</publisher-name>, <year>1994</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b79-80.4stein"><label>79.</label><note><p>For a more detailed discussion of this issue, including source material, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2064440"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), pp. <fpage>79</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>80</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b80-80.4stein"><label>80.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Schmid</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Kurtzer bericht</italic></source> (n. 54), p. <fpage>144</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b81-80.4stein"><label>81.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Foucault</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Birth of the Clinic</italic></source> (n. 27), p. <fpage>12</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b82-80.4stein"><label>82.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Seitz</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Ein nutzlich regiment</italic></source> (n. 67), p. <fpage>11</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b83-80.4stein"><label>83.</label><note><p>It was a central premise of Aristotelian natural philosophy that women's complexions were generally more humid and colder than men's. For a thoughtful discussion of the various ideas on the difference between women and men in the medieval and early modern periods, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2064a40"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Joan</surname><given-names>Cadden</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Meanings of Sex Difference in the Middle Ages: Medicine, Science, and Culture</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1993</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b84-80.4stein"><label>84.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Von Hutten</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Holtz Guaiacum</italic></source> (n. 42), p. <fpage>476</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b85-80.4stein"><label>85.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Knobloch</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>De Lue Venerea</italic></source> (n. 61), p. <fpage>123</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b86-80.4stein"><label>86.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2064ec0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Magnus</surname><given-names>Hundt</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Eyn kurtzes vnd sehr nutzbarlichs Regiment wider dye schwynde vnd erschreckliche kranckheit der Pestilentz &#x02026; Meher eyn nutzlichs Regiment wider die weltleuftige un[d] vnsauber kranckheit der Frantzosen</italic></source> (Magdeburg, <year>1529</year>), <comment>fol. 19<sup>v</sup></comment></citation> For the identity of the physician Magnus Hundt, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2064fe0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source> (n. 2), p. <fpage>31</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b87-80.4stein"><label>87.</label><note><p>For the understanding of the pox within the micro-macrocosm framework, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2065160"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source><comment>(n. 2), pp.</comment><fpage>39</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>52</lpage></citation>. For an introduction, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x2065280"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Mary</surname><given-names>Lindemann</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Medicine and Society in Early Modern Europe</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1999</year>), p. <fpage>20</fpage></citation>. See also <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x20653a0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Michel</surname><given-names>Foucault</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Order of Things: An Archaeology of the Human Sciences</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>London</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Routledge</publisher-name>, <year>2003</year>), esp. chaps. 1 and 2, pp. <fpage>3</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>50</lpage></citation>. For the importance of astrology in early modern medicine, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x20654c0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Allan</surname><given-names>Chapmann</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Astrological Medicine,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>Health, Medicine and Mortality</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Charles</surname><given-names>Webster</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Cambridge</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Cambridge University Press</publisher-name>, <year>1979</year>), pp. <fpage>175</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>200</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b88-80.4stein"><label>88.</label><note><p>SA, Karton VI, no. 47, Prod. 67.</p></note></ref><ref id="b89-80.4stein"><label>89.</label><note><p>Ibid., Prod. 23.</p></note></ref><ref id="b90-80.4stein"><label>90.</label><note><p>Ibid., Prod. 44.</p></note></ref><ref id="b91-80.4stein"><label>91.</label><note><p>Ibid., Prod. 43.</p></note></ref><ref id="b92-80.4stein"><label>92.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Fries</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Spiegel der Artzney</italic></source><comment>(n. 33), fol. 4<sup>r</sup></comment></citation></ref><ref id="b93-80.4stein"><label>93.</label><note><p>&#x0201c;Dieweil vil unbeschichketer schaden sein, darbey sy gehailt vnd gesund gemacht werden kain hoffnung ist &#x02026; darbey zu besorgen, das aller uncost vnnd arztney mue vnd arbeitt verloren sey&#x0201d; (Blatterhaus, Ordnung von 1522, SA).</p></note></ref><ref id="b94-80.4stein"><label>94.</label><note><p>Once appointed, most medical practitioners continued to work in the hospital until they retired or died. For more details, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34090"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source><comment>(n. 2), pp.</comment><fpage>238</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>39</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b95-80.4stein"><label>95.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34210"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Nance</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Turquet de Mayerne</italic></source><comment>(n. 19), p.</comment><fpage>98</fpage></citation>. See also <citation citation-type="journal" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34330"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Brian</surname><given-names>Nance</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Determining the Patient's Temperament: An Excursion into Seventeenth-Century Medical Semiology,&#x0201d;</article-title><source><italic>Bull. Hist. Med.</italic></source>, <year>1993</year>, <volume>67</volume> : <fpage>417</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>88</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">8219704</pub-id></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b96-80.4stein"><label>96.</label><note><p><citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3f344b0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Shigehisa</surname><given-names>Kuriyama</given-names></name></person-group>, <article-title>&#x0201c;Pulse Diagnostic in the Greek and Chinese Traditions,&#x0201d;</article-title> in <source><italic>History of Diagnostics: Proceedings of the 9th International Symposium on the Comparative History of Medicine, East and West</italic></source>, ed. <person-group person-group-type="editor"><name><surname>Y.</surname><given-names>Kawakita</given-names></name></person-group> (<publisher-loc>Osaka</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Tangiguchio Foundation</publisher-name>, <year>1987</year>), pp. <fpage>43</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>67</lpage></citation>. See also <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34690"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Kuriyama</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>The Expressiveness of the Body and the Divergence of Greek and Chinese Medicine</italic></source> (<publisher-loc>New York</publisher-loc>: <publisher-name>Zone Books</publisher-name>, <year>1999</year>).</citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b97-80.4stein"><label>97.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Nance</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Turquet de Mayerne</italic></source> (n. 19), p. <fpage>98</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b98-80.4stein"><label>98.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Von Hutten</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Holtz Guaicum</italic></source> (n. 42), p. <fpage>406</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b99-80.4stein"><label>99.</label><note><p>For this case see SA, Karton VI, no. 47, Prod. 35.</p></note></ref><ref id="b100-80.4stein"><label>100.</label><note><p>For this institution and its admissions rules, see <citation citation-type="book" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34b70"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Stein</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Franzosenkrankheit</italic></source><comment>(n. 2), pp.</comment><fpage>105</fpage>&#x02013;<lpage>7</lpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b101-80.4stein"><label>101.</label><note><p>For the biographies of sixteenth-century Augsburg physicians, see <citation citation-type="thesis" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34cf0"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Elisabeth</surname><given-names>Martz</given-names></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Gesundheitswesen und &#x000c4;rzte in Augsburg im 16. Jahrhundert</italic></source> (med. diss., Munich, <year>1950</year>)</citation>. For more biographical details on <citation citation-type="other" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34e10"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Leopold</surname><given-names>Trenklin</given-names></name></person-group> (also Drinkel or Trinkel), see p. <fpage>30</fpage></citation>; on <citation citation-type="other" id="N0x2431540N0x3f34f30"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Marcus</surname><given-names>Wind</given-names></name></person-group>, p. <fpage>36</fpage></citation>; on <citation citation-type="other" id="N0x2431540N0x3f35050"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Bernhard</surname><given-names>Schludi</given-names></name></person-group>, p. <fpage>27</fpage></citation></p></note></ref><ref id="b102-80.4stein"><label>102.</label><citation citation-type="book"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Foucault</surname></name></person-group>, <source><italic>Order of Things</italic></source> (n. 87), p. <fpage>36</fpage></citation></ref><ref id="b103-80.4stein"><label>103.</label><note><p>I have given the socioeconomic discourses and practices more thought and attention in my recent monograph (n. 2). Based on that research I am inclined to think that, due to the flexibility of early modern disease definition, generalizations as to the identity of the pox are virtually impossible. More microhistorical studies than this one, I submit, would show that disease identity in the early modern period was always distinctively local. What the pox was&#x02014;that is, how it was perceived, talked about, and distinguished from other diseases&#x02014;ultimately depended on the specific sociocultural environment, the various terrains of discourse and practice surrounding disease phenomena within the specific local setting in which they occurred.</p></note></ref></ref-list></back></article>





